00:07:02,178 --> 00:07:07,190
We must think of how we will make
sure that our product complies

105
00:07:07,378 --> 00:07:11,103
with what has been specified
in the previous points.

106
00:07:11,604 --> 00:07:16,892
If a specification is not very
viable it is not adequate. 

107
00:07:17,241 --> 00:07:23,141
There are many rubrics in this list
but it is still not exhaustive, but our

108
00:07:23,337 --> 00:07:27,612
hope is that it helps you ask
yourself the right questions.

109
00:07:28,215 --> 00:07:31,453
Our next strategic
topic is partnerships.

110
00:07:31,814 --> 00:07:35,201
This is of course a very valid
question in all of the product

111
00:07:35,397 --> 00:07:37,659
value chains segments.

112
00:07:37,892 --> 00:07:42,867
But we decided to insist on it,
especially in this one, as it is

113
00:07:43,051 --> 00:07:45,289
where it is often overlooked.

114
00:07:45,476 --> 00:07:49,750
Inventors like to do things
themselves, and this is fine

115
00:07:49,927 --> 00:07:54,302
as long as we are not missing an
opportunity to be more efficient.

116
00:07:54,493 --> 00:07:59,231
Projects could often be accelerated
if we were able to overcome

117
00:07:59,404 --> 00:08:03,754
the infamous "not invented here"
syndrome.

118
00:08:04,364 --> 00:08:09,152
Procter & Gamble has famously tried
to correct this very human behavior

119
00:08:09,332 --> 00:08:14,257
by promoting the motto:
"Proudly found elsewhere".

120
00:08:14,444 --> 00:08:18,031
We should never refrain from
partnering in the interest of our

121
00:08:18,201 --> 00:08:21,876
objective, because an efficient product
development partnership

122
00:08:22,053 --> 00:08:26,028
can make you avoid years
of painstaking work.

123
00:08:27,289 --> 00:08:31,827
We have also repeatedly insisted
on the importance of collaborating

124
00:08:32,006 --> 00:08:35,006
with local partners and
across disciplines.

125
00:08:35,312 --> 00:08:38,887
There is hardly any moment
when it is more important than

126
00:08:39,063 --> 00:08:41,350
in the early phases
of a project.

127
00:08:41,527 --> 00:08:45,665
We need to ask ourselves
who could be a good partner?

128
00:08:46,132 --> 00:08:49,918
It could be an institution,
a company, an NGO

129
00:08:50,106 --> 00:08:52,543
or simply an individual.

130
00:08:52,718 --> 00:08:57,804
Another important topic is related
to standards and regulations.

131
00:08:57,983 --> 00:09:01,283
Getting into details would
take another MOOC.

132
00:09:01,457 --> 00:09:06,481
Broadly speaking, a standard is
a set of rules which define

133
00:09:06,642 --> 00:09:10,942
a preconceived way to design
or test some product.

134
00:09:11,392 --> 00:09:15,791
Standards are generally developed
by organizations such as

135
00:09:15,968 --> 00:09:19,442
the International Standards
Organization or the ISO, or

136
00:09:19,606 --> 00:09:24,381
the International Electrical
Commission or IEC.

137
00:09:24,625 --> 00:09:29,000
The application of standards is
generally voluntary, but can

138
00:09:29,168 --> 00:09:34,855
become mandatory if adopted by
a government through legislation.

139
00:09:35,161 --> 00:09:40,048
In Europe and some other places,
products are required to beat

140
00:09:40,228 --> 00:09:47,040
the CE mark, formally this indicates
that the product complies with

141
00:09:47,204 --> 00:09:51,329
the European legislation
for that category of products.

142
00:09:51,561 --> 00:09:55,810
This does not necessarily mean
that the product complies to all

143
00:09:55,984 --> 00:09:59,659
technical standards existing
for that product category,

144
00:09:59,835 --> 00:10:02,184
but certainly to some of them.

145
00:10:02,365 --> 00:10:06,139
We will need to check for
our target country or region

146
00:10:06,321 --> 00:10:09,583
what the legal requirements are
for our product.

147
00:10:09,792 --> 00:10:14,391
This can sometimes be time
consuming and expensive, especially

148
00:10:14,573 --> 00:10:17,985
when the countries define
their own rules to protect

149
00:10:18,156 --> 00:10:20,518
their local industries.

150
00:10:20,687 --> 00:10:24,798
Another challenge is that the standards
have evolved with the progress made

151
00:10:24,971 --> 00:10:29,670
in industrialized countries and may
not be well adapted to the situation

152
00:10:29,856 --> 00:10:32,406
in low and middle income countries.

153
00:10:33,367 --> 00:10:37,891
Now we would like to discuss
a crucial ethical issue.

154
00:10:38,065 --> 00:10:42,139
It is not because some low income
countries have loopholes

155
00:10:42,307 --> 00:10:44,806
in their legislation that we should

156
00:10:44,977 --> 00:10:47,626
neglect the compliance
with key standards

157
00:10:47,802 --> 00:10:49,526
for our product.

158
00:10:49,705 --> 00:10:55,042
We don't want to develop poor
technologies for poor countries.

159
00:10:55,216 --> 00:10:59,003
In spite of the challenge,
we strongly believe that

160
00:10:59,181 --> 00:11:03,455
every human being deserves
the same level of product quality

161
00:11:03,627 --> 00:11:06,627
safety and effectiveness.

162
00:11:06,961 --> 00:11:12,023
We need to resist the temptation of
making short-cuts and neglecting

163
00:11:12,193 --> 00:11:17,555
relevant standards, even if it makes
the project much more difficult.

164
00:11:17,965 --> 00:11:21,652
We give you a simple rule
to know if you have achieved

165
00:11:21,836 --> 00:11:25,161
a sufficient level of
safety and effectiveness.

166
00:11:25,768 --> 00:11:28,543
Would you be allowed to
sell your technology in

167
00:11:28,723 --> 00:11:30,961
an industrialized country?

168
00:11:31,218 --> 00:11:34,218
If the answer is yes,
then you're fine.

169
00:11:34,728 --> 00:11:37,827
Our best advice is to have a good
discussion with people who

170
00:11:37,998 --> 00:11:41,348
know this subject early
on in your project.

171
00:11:41,709 --> 00:11:46,233
Also, a lot of relevant information
can be found on the internet.

172
00:11:46,418 --> 00:11:49,818
For example, on
the website of the IEC.

173
00:11:50,433 --> 00:11:54,258
Another important topic is
intellectual property protection.

174
00:11:54,602 --> 00:11:57,752
Here as well the subject
would require another MOOC.

175
00:11:58,401 --> 00:12:02,387
I will not discuss trademarks
or copyrights but concentrate

176
00:12:02,562 --> 00:12:04,237
on patents.

177
00:12:04,431 --> 00:12:08,430
Patents are intended
as incentive to invent.

178
00:12:08,607 --> 00:12:12,844
A patent is a means by which
the authorities grant the inventor

179
00:12:13,013 --> 00:12:17,212
a time limited exclusivity for
the commercial exploitation 

180
00:12:17,388 --> 00:12:20,375
of his or her invention.

181
00:12:20,541 --> 00:12:24,616
the process of filing and
managing a patent is complex

182
00:12:24,781 --> 00:12:28,381
and support from a specialist
is generally required.

183
00:12:29,011 --> 00:12:32,423
However, we have to carefully
think about our strategy

184
00:12:32,597 --> 00:12:37,785
regarding patents before hand,
because they are very expensive.

185
00:12:37,973 --> 00:12:43,385
Not only are the filing costs high,
but there also many additional fees

186
00:12:43,559 --> 00:12:47,083
that will have to be paid all
along the patents lifetime,

187
00:12:47,258 --> 00:12:50,258
which is limited to twenty years.

188
00:12:50,525 --> 00:12:53,987
Over it's lifetime a patent
filed in a dozen countries

189
00:12:54,169 --> 00:12:58,380
can easily cost up to several
hundred thousand dollars in total

190
00:12:58,570 --> 00:13:02,458
and this does not even
include potential litigation.

191
00:13:03,012 --> 00:13:08,537
The costs must really be offset by
the benefits obtained from

192
00:13:08,715 --> 00:13:11,103
the patents exclusivity rights.

193
00:13:11,283 --> 00:13:15,608
It is, thus, fundamental to ask
yourself if a protection offered

194
00:13:15,784 --> 00:13:18,159
by a patent is worthwhile.

195
00:13:18,718 --> 00:13:23,280
Also, you will have to designate
the countries in which you want to

196
00:13:23,465 --> 00:13:26,252
request protection
for your invention.

197
00:13:26,433 --> 00:13:30,295
Every additional country
or region will increase costs.

198
00:13:30,901 --> 00:13:35,575
On the contrary, you may decide
not to pursue any patent protection

199
00:13:35,754 --> 00:13:40,429
at all, and leave the invention
open for everyone to use.

200
00:13:41,497 --> 00:13:44,497
There is a downside to
this strategy, however.

201
00:13:44,808 --> 00:13:49,320
At a later stage you will perhaps
want to involve investors and they

202
00:13:49,504 --> 00:13:54,404
usually like to see patents, because
they are barriers to entry for your

203
00:13:54,605 --> 00:13:59,779
competitors, it is a way to keep
your company competitive and

204
00:13:59,984 --> 00:14:03,147
sustainable, so there is
a balance to be found.

205
00:14:03,623 --> 00:14:07,397
On the other hand, in case
of infringement of your patent

206
00:14:07,572 --> 00:14:10,471
defending it against an
an unfair competitor 

207
00:14:10,650 --> 00:14:15,150
could cost you years of litigation,
which could lead to bankruptcy.

208
00:14:15,783 --> 00:14:18,995
There is one additional important
thing we need to keep in mind.

209
00:14:19,179 --> 00:14:22,528
Any public disclosure of
an invention before it has been

210
00:14:22,704 --> 00:14:26,842
filed will prevent you from
seeking patent protection.

211
00:14:27,394 --> 00:14:31,968
This public disclosure could be
in the form of publication in

212
00:14:32,158 --> 00:14:36,270
a news paper, on the internet,
or simply a poster placed in

213
00:14:36,457 --> 00:14:38,157
a public location.

214
00:14:38,767 --> 00:14:43,579
We have to be especially careful
with our partners as they sometimes

215
00:14:43,753 --> 00:14:46,452
disclose things inadvertently.

216
00:14:46,633 --> 00:14:50,344
Conversely, if you do not want
to patent your invention

217
00:14:50,526 --> 00:14:54,038
you should disclose it publicly,
as otherwise someone could

218
00:14:54,219 --> 00:14:58,093
come along and file a patent on your
invention, which he could then use

219
00:14:58,278 --> 00:14:59,541
against you.

220
00:14:59,724 --> 00:15:03,311
This tactic is called
defensive publishing.

221
00:15:03,718 --> 00:15:07,018
As you may find out,
your idea may have already

222
00:15:07,212 --> 00:15:09,274
been patented before.

223
00:15:09,744 --> 00:15:12,706
This could entitle someone
else to prevent you from

224
00:15:12,880 --> 00:15:15,604
using your innovation
or to claim payments

225
00:15:15,799 --> 00:15:17,123
or royalties.

226
00:15:17,310 --> 00:15:21,609
To anticipate this problem you need
to assess your freedom to operate.

227
00:15:21,796 --> 00:15:25,583
An easy way to check if
a patent is still enforced

228
00:15:25,777 --> 00:15:28,701
is to look at the so
called priority date.

229
00:15:28,876 --> 00:15:33,588
If the date is over twenty years ago
you're most probably fine.

230
00:15:33,888 --> 00:15:37,912
It could also be that the inventor
has stopped paying the fees and

231
00:15:38,084 --> 00:15:43,022
the patent is no longer valid, even
if it is less than twenty years old.

232
00:15:44,310 --> 00:15:48,347
It is also important to check if
the filing was done in your target

233
00:15:48,528 --> 00:15:50,577
country or region.

234
00:15:50,754 --> 00:15:54,978
It could be that a specific patent
has been filed in a high income

235
00:15:55,159 --> 00:15:57,671
country only because
the patent owner

236
00:15:57,842 --> 00:16:02,667
did not consider the others as
potentially interesting markets.

237
00:16:03,467 --> 00:16:07,941
There are searchable databases
on the patents on the internet,

238
00:16:08,119 --> 00:16:13,319
which allow you to see if
a specific patent is still active.

